sample size was number of recorded cells. For all image data, sample size was the number of images except for frequency histo-
grams in Figures 5E, S5C, and S5F, where sample size was the number of analyzed ROIs. Image data are presented as violin plots
with superimposed mean ± SEM throughout, except for datasets with % 40 images. Wild-type controls in Figures 2C, 2D, and 2G (in
which all values are close to 0) are shown as scatterplots because violin plots would be non-informative. For microdialysis data, sam-
ple size was the number of mice. Datasets with sample size R 30 were analyzed using parametric statistical tests. For datasets with
sample size < 30, normality was determined with Anderson-Darling, D’Agostino-Pearson, Shapiro-Wilk, or one sample Kolmogorov-
Smirnov tests and statistics were performed using non-parametric tests for datasets that did not follow a normal distribution. In all
ﬁgures, statistical signiﬁcance is presented as * p < 0.05, ** p < 0.01, *** p < 0.001.
